    <h3 id="equipment-2">Equipment</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Mobile device (tablet/phone) with the Monitor app
pre-loaded</p></li>
<li><p>GNSS, such as a Trimble R1 or DA2 receiver, a hand-held GPS or
device built-in GPS (least preferred), capable of achieving &lt;30 cm
accuracy</p></li>
<li><p>DSLR camera and micro SD card(s) (optional)</p></li>
<li><p>Large tools (long-handled shovel, spade, mattock, crowbar,
axe)</p></li>
<li><p>Soil auger (Jarrett hand auger 75 mm) with 10 cm depths marked on
the handle</p></li>
<li><p>Small tools (trowel, geo pick, lump hammer, secateurs, wire
scrubbing brush, paint brush)</p></li>
<li><p>Ground sheet and sheet to protect exposed soil face
(optional)</p></li>
<li><p>15–20 large sized zip-lock bags per plot (27 x 33 cm; white block
for labelling)</p></li>
<li><p>Large plastic bag per plot to store individual samples together
(ca. 50 x 60 cm)</p></li>
<li><p>Voucher barcode labels (see the Generating Voucher Barcode Labels
for EMSA Specimens and Samples instruction sheet)</p></li>
<li><p>Pit tape (2 m)</p></li>
<li><p>Spray bottle with water</p></li>
<li><p>Towel (for cleaning equipment and hands)</p></li>
<li><p>Soil sieve (2 mm) and base tray</p></li>
<li><p>Permanent marker</p></li>
<li><p>Australian Soil and Land Classification Handbook (Yellow Book;
NCST 2009)</p></li>
</ul>"""^^rdf:HTML ;
    tern:instructions """
    <h3 id="instructions-and-procedures-2">Instructions and procedures</h3>
<ol type="1">
<li><p>Ensure the <a href="https://linked.data.gov.au/def/nrm/d15d05db-5007-411e-b257-105ef4f76821">Plot Selection and Layout Module</a> has been completed to
mark out the plot boundary and define the current plot and visit in the
Monitor app.</p></li>
</ol>
<ol start="2" type="1">
<li><p>Select <em>Soils Module</em> &gt; <em>Soil sample pit
protocol</em>.</p></li>
<li><p>Navigate to just outside the southwest corner of the plot. Select
<em>record the soil sample pit location</em>. The app will automatically
record the <em>soil sample pit ID</em>, the project and current survey,
along with the location details.</p></li>
<li><p>Record the <em>observation type</em> being used to expose the
soil profile.</p></li>
<li><p>Dig a soil pit to 1 m+ deep or to depth of limiting layer (see <a href="#soil-pit">Additional guidelines</a>). Place the spoil on a ground
sheet to minimise disturbance and assist backfilling. Record the
<em>soil pit depth (m)</em> of the soil pit.</p></li>
<li><p>If a depth of 1 m+ cannot be achieved, record what digging was
<em>stopped by</em>.</p></li>
<li><p>Assess which face of the pit is best for photographing, taking
into consideration angle of the sun and shadows. Position the pit tape
on the left or right edge of the best face and select the <em>soil pit
photo</em> button to capture an image using your device's camera.
Alternatively, an external camera can be used to take the photo. See <a href="#soil-pit">Additional guidelines</a>.</p></li>
<li><p>Record <em>soil pit comments</em>, this could include soil
surface descriptions, where the pit is located in the context of the
plot, any site disturbances, vegetation community or plant species
around the pit, soil characteristics that might be present (coarse
fragments, moisture, abrupt changes in texture or colour down the soil
profile, discernible layers in the soil profile).</p></li>
<li><p>Prepare a soil sample zip-lock bag for each 10 cm soil depth
increment in the pit. Use a permanent marker to write the plot code,
date of collection and soil depth increment. Place a barcode label on
each sample bag in sequential order.</p></li>
<li><p>Select the <em>scan barcode</em> button to scan the barcode label
on the sample.</p></li>
<li><p>Collect a 10 cm soil depth 500 g soil sample and place into the
labelled zip-lock bag. Use the pit tape to determine the
increments.</p></li>
<li><p>Record the corresponding <em>sample interval (m)</em> from the
dropdown list. If the interval does not appear in the list, select
<em>new interval</em> and manually enter the upper and lower depths in
metres.</p></li>
<li><p>Record any <em>sample comments</em>, this could include horizon
or layer if known, if the sample has coarse fragments (type, abundance),
indication of texture, the soil moisture at time of collecting.</p></li>
<li><p>Save the soil sample and select + button to collect and record
the next sample.</p></li>
<li><p>Repeat steps 10-14 for each 10 cm soil depth increment down the
soil profile.</p></li>
<li><p>Store all samples together in a large plastic bag labelled with
plot code and date collected.</p></li>
<li><p>To save and review the protocol select <em>complete soil pit
sampling</em> then select <em>edit this collection</em> to make any
changes required.</p></li>
<li><p>If you are collecting bulk density samples, prior to backfilling
the soil pit undertake the <a href="#soil-bulk-density">Soil bulk
density protocol</a>, which collects soil bulk density samples from an
edge of the pit.</p></li>
</ol>"""^^rdf:HTML ;
